
[1]spleen

   SPLEEN, n. [L., Gr.]

   1. The milt; a soft part of the viscera of animals, whose use is not
   well understood. The ancients supposed this to be the seat of
   melancholy, anger or vexation. Hence,

   2. Anger; latent spite; ill humor. Thus we say, to vent ones spleen.

   In noble minds some dregs remain, Not yet purged off, of spleen and
   sour disdain.

   3. A fit of anger.

   4. A fit; a sudden motion. [Not used.]

   5. Melancholy; hypochondriacal affections.

   --Bodies changd to recent forms by spleen.

   6. Immoderate merriment. [Not in use.]
